\pard\plain \fi360\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Mandrameen was a poet and Seculla was a trial lawyer. It might seem that these two callings are as distant from each other as Man is from Woman, but according to Seculla, they were essentially the same. A poet and a lawyer both play with the Truth and appeal to human nature. The poet crafts verse and hopes that it will sing when played on the human heart, and the lawyer does the same, just does it more bluntly, with less rhyming and more certainty. \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93We are poets whose audience settles matters of life and death,\u8221\'94 she\u8217\'92d say. \u8220\'93That\u8217\'92s the only real difference. That and the fact that a lawyer gets paid by the hour.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Whenever Mandrameen would lay with Seculla he\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92d tease her about this. He would say, with a great deal of comic exaggeration, that if a lawyer is just a poet working for money then a lawyer is no better than a whore. Money cheapens Virtue. A whore cheapens Love. A lawyer cheapens the Truth. }
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Seculla would wave him off with her usual air of grace. She\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92d argue that there\u8217\'92s no such thing as the Truth. A single murder recounted by three different witnesses will result in three different stories. Unless there\u8217\'92s a bloody knife in hand we are all invincibly ignorant. Almost everything boils down to a he-said she-said, and everyone picks a side. Might as well get paid to do it. At least a lawyer\u8217\'92s accounting of the Truth is put through peer review. }
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 It is little wonder that the two disagreed on how Jeketian society should be structured. Mandrameen believed that morality was written on the hearts of men. He believed in Humans were endowed by the Gods with natural rights. The Law should emanate from these and protect them. Seculla would say that it didn\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92t matter what anyone }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 thought}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  the law should be, there\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s only what it is: a practical thing for resolving disputes, and it is subject to circumstance, politics, and power. No one has anything by natural right; you only have what you can take for yourself, and you\u8217\'92ll have it for as long as you can defend it. The only law written on the hearts of men is that of Self-Interest.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Perhaps if Seculla had been alive to see the dynamics within Ayram\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s band, she might not have been so quick to doubt that Humanity has an intrinsic moral compass. Perhaps if Mandrameen had seen it, he might not have liked the direction that the compass's needle was pointing. It didn\u8217\'92t point to Liberty or Virtue, it pointed to Ayram.}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://A276867B-71C2-46AA-86BA-5CD3BCA1605D"}{\fldrslt\f1\fs24\b0\i0  He was a Law unto himself. }}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Split up!\u8221\'94 he shouted, his voice echoing round the pit. }
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Hill grabbed the scruff of Pyetle\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s cloak and pulled him up, then led him to one side of the pit. There they were surrounded by all the other men. On the other side of the pit were the women.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Pella!\u8221\'94 Ayram barked. Pella then led the women, about ten of them, into the cave. Ayram followed.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Where are they going?\u8221\'94 Pyetle asked Hill.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93You want to find out?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Yes. You mean you don\u8217\'92t know?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93I never asked.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 A gruff voice behind them in spoke. \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93It\u8217\'92s ain\u8217\'92t your business to ask what Ayram do with the women.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Sob is right.\u8221\'94 Hill said. \u8220\'93Pyetle, this is Sob.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Pyetle turned. Sob was standing close. He was a tall, scrawny man. A rugged Northerner. His thin face was twisted uniformly to the left as if something had knocked it that way as a babe and it just kept growing in that direction. It was so askew that even though he was looking straight down at Pyetle, one of his eyes was blocked by his nose, which was nearly in profile. }
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Well, then what is it we\u8217\'92re doing?\u8221\'94 Pyetle asked.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93I\u8217\'92m gonna get you out o\u8217\'92 those tatters,\u8221\'94 said Sob. \u8220\'93Go on.\u8221\'94 He pointed to a wicker basket. It was sitting in the shade of a tarred leather canvas. It was filled past the brim with shirts, cloaks, and woolen wraps.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Whose are those?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93They be Ayrams.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93I wont fit in those.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93No. Everything\u8217\'92s Ayram\u8217\'92s \u8216\'91ere. Cloths on me back. Even your tatters. Go on. Pick summat out.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Pyetle walked over and dug through the basket. He pulled out the few things that looked like they would fit: a light linen tunic that was crumpled with salt and sweat, a pair of brown leather pants with a stripe sewn vertically down the sides, and a pair of rawhide sandals that perfectly fit. The shirt had a blood stain around the collar.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Those be Papi\u8217\'92s things.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93I thought you said they were Ayram\u8217\'92s.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Don\u8217\'92t get smaht. Papi was wearin \u8216\'91em. Everything\u8217\'92s Ayram\u8217\'92s.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Well who is Papi?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Papillian? Lad\u8217\'92s dead now. Not three days, yet.\u8221\'94 Sob\u8217\'92s mouth twisted into a smile. \u8220\'93He was wearin yorn clothes, he was.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93I don\u8217\'92t suppose you\u8217\'92ve got anything else.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93You\u8217\'92ve still got the cloak,\u8221\'94 Hill said optimistically. \u8220\'93It\u8217\'92s saved you once.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Did it, now?\u8221\'94 Sob asked. Hill nodded.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Yes, he\u8217\'92s got a lucky cloak.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93A lucky cloak, does he? Well now he\u8217\'92s got unlucky everything else, I think.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Maybe my luck will even out,\u8221\'94 Pyetle said.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Sob slapped him on the back. \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Not sure it works thatta way, Pyetle,\u8221\'94 he said. \u8220\'93You either got good luck or bad luck. No such thing as \u8216\'91no luck\u8217\'92, cause that\u8217\'92s just bad luck.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93You have good luck?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Oi, right I do, right I do. It\u8217\'92s my coins that do it.\u8221\'94 Sob shook a bag of coins that was strung to his belt. \u8220\'93I count them whenever things start to get irey.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93How much you got?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93A full siver-string if you could believe it.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Pyetle\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s eyes widened. }
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93You carry that around wherever you go?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93He does.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Oi. They me lucky coins.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93What if Ayram wanted them.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93What?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Well, they\u8217\'92re not your coins, right? They\u8217\'92re Ayram\u8217\'92s. You said -\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93What are you all on my coins fer?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Calm down, Sob.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Hold on, Hill. I want to know what he\u8217\'92s on my coins fer.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93He new blood, Sob. Calm down.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Sob leaned down and put his face close to Pyelte\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s and said, \u8220\'93I kin see \u8216\'91round corners.\u8221\'94 He turned his head to the right to show that he really could. \u8220\'93Don\u8217\'92t you try anythin\u8217\'92 on me coins or anythin else.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Okay, Sob. Fetch the Seilsi some clothes.\u8221\'94}
